@node "Introduction"
@next "Author"

@{b}@{i}Introduction@{ui}@{ub} :

HLink is a serial communication and transfer tool for all amiga's. The only
other thing needed is a serial @{i}null-modem@{ui} cable. There are no further
libraries or devices needed becides the standard ones. The installation is
very simple and the program can be started after a few activities.

I know that there are an lot off 'network' like programs, some of wich very
reliable. On the other hand, it sometimes takes ages to install them
properly or when installed it just don't offers what you need.

So here is my contribution, a easy to install program with some nice
features and all for free. Check it out, it might or might not be usefull
but offers some usefull functions for anyone needing them.

Myself use it for a number of reasons. Firstly because I had it up to there
sliding from one system to the other simply because the needed data was not
at the right place or a guest-user had a request. No I can do this from
my one workplace without bothering the guest.

Secondly, there are a hand full of programs that take complete control of
the system without given you a chance of using workbench or CLI. The only
sollution at that moment is to quit that program. In some situations I can
imagine it beeing frustating, for example in the middle of a "This takes to
long so do it once" render session.

I hope you enjoy this product,


                                                Michael D.P. de Clerck

@endnode



@node "Features"

@{b}@{i}Features@{ui}@{ub} :

Since the last version of HLink there has been some changes, there are
new commands, better routines and of course fixed bugs.

The memory needed to communicate is roughly 400 Kb, for file transfer the
amount of needed memory is roughly equal to 400 Kb + filesize.

This program works best on an harddisk based systems. It can also be used 
on floppy based systems but at least 1MB of memory is advised.

Here is a list of the features of @{b}Handy Link 2.0@{ub} :

The first nice thing is that all the controlling is done from any dos-shell,
the ability to perform normal dos commands and HLink commando's in the same
shell improves the orientation of the user.


 @{"Status window      " Link ""} - Seperate window for status & reports.
 @{"Chatting           " Link "Chat"} - Talking with the remote station.
 @{"Remote DOS control " Link "Remote DOS Commands"} - Entering remote Amiga DOS commands.
 @{"Command buffer     " Link ""} - A buffer of the last used commands, only >WB2.0.
 @{"File transfer      " Link "File Transfer"} - Transmitting/receiving files/
 @{"Lowmemory transfer " Link "Lowmem transfer"} - Spare memory by using file-2-file transfer.
 @{"HLink Scripts      " Link "HLink Scripts"} - Batchscript processing (Local & Remote)
 @{"Network scripts    " Link "Net Scripts"} - Network-like environment use.
 @{"Automatic transfer " Link "Auto transfer"} - Full automatic transfer of files.
 @{"Search & Send      " Link "HLink Syntaxes"} - Get {remote-file} command.


@endnode



@node "Installation"

@{b}@{i}Installation@{ui}@{ub} :

The installation of HLink can be performed automaticly or manually.
For automatic installation use the @{i}HLink2.Install@{ui} script with the
@{fg highlightInstaller@{fg text} command from your Workbench disk

Follows these steps :

Copy the file HLink2.Lha to RAM: and dearchive it using :

 > Lha -X RAM:HLink2.Lha RAM:


Now the following files should be available and copied to a directory :

  HLink                 - The main program.
  HLink.Guide           - This Amigaguide documentation.
  HLink.Config          - The configuration file,
  Install_HLink         - The installation script.
  HLink.Shell-Startup   - The Shell-Startup lines for HLink.
  HLink.User-Startup    - The User-Startup lines for HLink.
  Join                  - The file joni command.
  Print.hl              - A HLink remote scri example.

  NetScripts            - Remote application script examples.

HLink uses 4 directory's to forfill it's tasks. here is an list of those
directory's :

  HLink:              - This is the program directory.

  HL:                 - This directory is used for the command and chat lines,
                        It is selected often so should be in the RAM: disk.
                        Do NOT place it in the root of the RAM disk cause the
                        files might be mistaken for system files, make an child-
                        directory instead and assign HL: to it.

  D:                  - This directory is the default for transferring files
                        and the saving of the erorlog file.

  SD:                 - This directory is used as automatic file transfer
                        directory.



Add the following line to you S:startup-sequence or S:user-startup file :

  assign HLink:  {path}  - The path where the program files are placed

  assign HL:     RAM:    - The work directory of HLink, can be disk or RAM,
                           this directory will also be temporarely used for
                           placing the autotransfer files.

  assign D:      {path}  - The default transfer directory for receiving and
                           sending. This assign name can be changed in the
                           @{"HLink.Config" Link "HLink Syntaxes"} file.
                           HLink.config file.

  assign SD:     {path}  - The automatic transfer directory.
                           This assign name can be changed in the
                           @{"HLink.Config" Link "HLink Syntaxes"} file.



Add the following lines to your S:shell-startup file to enable command
redirectini to HLink :

  alias com   "Echo >> HL:execute"
  alias chat  "Echo >> HL:chat"


Make sure that the file "serial.device" exists in the Devs: directory and
that it is mounted. Now Hlink can be started by running it from the shell
or the workbench.


@{b}!NOTE@{ub} : If you want to use HLink without having to acces a drive for DOS
        commands then do the following following :

          - Make the following commands resident using (Only <WB2.0) :

              > RESIDENT >NIL: C:Echo PURE
              > RESIDENT >NIL: C:Copy PURE
              > RESIDENT >NIL: C:Delete PURE
              > RESIDENT >NIL: C:List PURE
              > RESIDENT >NIL: C:Protect PURE

          - Use the RAM disk for temporary workspace, ie. assign HL: to RAM:

@{b}!NOTE@{ub} : If you want an Date & Time notation at every transfer then make
        sure that the DATE commands is in the C: directory.

@endnode



@node "Starting up"

@{b}@{i}Starting up@{ui}@{ub} :

HLink is started from a shell or from the workbench.
Any default settings can be placed in the S:HLink.config file.

The program can be stopped using the @{fg highlight}Exit@{fg text} command or by pressing
the Ctrl+Esc keys.
@endnode



@node "HLink"

The HLink usage :

This chapter will describe the chat, command and transfer options of
HLink. All the control of HLink is done through the use of temporary
files, these are @{i}HL:Chat@{ui} and @{i}HL:Execute@{ui} and wich respectivily store
the chat text and the commands.
When there is time the files are processed and deleted.

All the commands are given from the @{"shell" Link "Shell Syntaxes"}, there
are two so'called alias commands to achive this. See installation part about
the @{i}S:Shell-Startup@{ui} file.

The first is the @{"Chat" Link "Chat"} command, this will redirect a textline
into to the chat file wich will be send to the remote station.

The second one is the @{"Com" Link "HLink Syntaxes"} command, this will
redirect a Amiga DOS or HLink command to the command file.
@endnode



@node "Shell Syntaxes"

@{b}@{i}The Shell syntaxes@{ui}@{ub} :

Following are the syntaxes of HLink commands to use from within a shell:

 Execute a local Amiga DOS command
 @{fg hightlight}> {Command} @{fg text}

 Send a @{"Chat" Link "Chat"} textline to the other station
 @{fg hightlight}> Chat  @{fg text}

 Execute a local @{"HLink command" Link "HLink Syntaxes"}
 @{fg hightlight}> Com {command} [parameters]  @{fg text}

 Execute a @{"remote DOS command" Link "Remote DOS Commands"}
 @{fg hightlight}> Com {DOS command}  @{fg text}

 Execute a remote @{"HLink command" Link "HLink Syntaxes"}
 @{fg hightlight}> Com #{command} [parameters]  @{fg text}

 Execute a remote @{"HLink script" Link "Hlink Scripts"}, always use extension '.al'
 @{fg hightlight}> com xxxxx.hl  @{fg text}

@endnode



@node "Chat"

@{b}@{i}Remote chatting@{ui}@{ub} :

Textlines can be as long as the Shell and RAM memory will allow, further
there is no restriction in the characters to be used.

The syntax to use is :

  @{fg highlight}> Chat This is just a line !@{fg text}


@endnode





@endnode

@node "HLink Syntaxes"

@{b}@{i}Handy Link syntaxes@{ui}@{ub} :

When using the commands with parameters DON'T forget to seperate them
using an space character !

The following HLink commands are available (precede using Com ) :

Help                       - Brings you to this documentation

Connect                    - Try's to connect to other station when running.

Exit                       - Close system down

Settings                   - Show the current user settings

Test                       - Starts serial testing procedure, also reset the
                             transfer flags.
Testoff                    - Cancels the testing procedure

Send    {file} [AS] [dest] - Send a file to the remote station, when no
                             path is given the file is read from the default
                             work path. The command works like the LIST
                             command from DOS, wildcards can be given and also
                             the ALL parameter works.

                             There is a possiblity to give a destination
                             directory or filename can be given.

                             To do this just add the pathname after the command,
                             eg. > Send D:test RAM:
                             To give a new filename enter AS {filename}
                             after the command, eg. > Send D:test AS file
                             To give both a path and a new filename enter
                             them both using the AS key.
                             eg. > Send D:test AS RAM:file

Give   {path}{file}        - Searches for the file(s) using the given wildcard
                             and transmits it/them, when no path is given the
                             search will be performed on all devices else the
                             search will be performed within the given path.
                             The filename is case-insensitive.
                             As wildcard sign a * is used. For example :

                               star* - all the files starting with  star
                               *.iff - all the files ending with   .iff
                               *.i*  - all the files containing    .i

Get    {path}{file}        - This is an remote GIVE command and makes the
                             remote station search for file(s) with the given
                             wildcard wich will then be transmitted back.
                             See the Give command for the wildcard usage.


The following commands are used to set the user settings :


Serspeed      {baudrate}   - Set serial baudrate
Serbuf        {buffersize} - Set serial buffer (bytes)        ! not yet !
Serbits       7/8          - Set serial data bits used        ! not yet !
Serstopbits   0/1/2        - Set serial stop bits used        ! not yet !
SetParity     -1/0/1/2/3   - Set serial parity                ! not yet !
Serialfast                 - Goto fast serial transfer mode
Serialslow                 - Goto normal serial transfer mode
Serblock      {size}       - Set serial datablock size in bytes ( 48..60000)


Reqprocess    on/off       - Ask before processing a command

MainExit      on/off       - Close both systems when quitting

Window        on/off       - Open/Close HLink message window,

Hidden        on/off       - Hides the communication window at all cost.

Setall        on/off       - If on all commands will be send to slaves

Chd           [+]{path}    - Set work directory,the + option is optional
                             and will extend the current path with the
                             given path.
                             When only the path is given (like 'Com RAM:')
                             the program will check if the path exists, if
                             so the word directory is changed. This works
                             with path exstensions also.

Errorlog      on/off       - When on the chat & command input is displayed
                             on the user screen (use Ctrl+W) and stored
                             in the file D:errorlog. When set to on it will
                             generate an small delay because everything that
                             is printed to the status window will also be
                             written to the ErrorLog file.

RequestAgain  on/off       - When this is set on, any unsuccesfull received
                             file will be request until received succesfull.

Autodelay     x            - Set the periodic time after wich HLink will autotransfer
                             all the files in the SD: directory. This period is set
                             in 1/50th of a second.


ETAdelay      x            - Sets the period for wich the transfer E.T.A. time
                             will be updated in the status window. The period is set
                             in 1/50th of a second with an minimum of 100 1/50th.

Delay         x            - Sets the system delay for file transfers, this program
                             is coded & tested on a boosted 1200. If any timeout
                             problems arise on lower machines this setting can
                             be of help by slowing down the timeout functions.
                             It is set in 1/50th of a second.

Beep          on/off       - Turns the transfer warning on/off, when starting/ending
                             or initiating a transfer a beep sound wiil be made.

Lowmem        on/off       - When this is set to on all transfer (on current station)
                             will be done directly from or to a file.
                             If set to off the file will be loaded into memory and
                             and transferred, if there is not enough memory to load
                             the file the transfer will be automaticly done direct
                             from file.

@endnode



@node "HLink Configuration"

@{b}@{i}HLink Configuration@{ui}@{ub} :

This chapter will describe the configuration possibility's. When HLink is
started it will search for the @{i}HLink.Config@{ui} file in the @{i}S:@{ui} directory.

This file may contain any of thecommands to set some of the user settings,
the command and it's parameters must be seperated by one space.


The commands are to be used something like this :

Name {name}                - Sets the station name
Serspeed {baudrate}        - Sets the serial speed
Serblock {bytes}           - Sets the serial datablock size
Window X/Y/Width/Height    - Turns the message window on using coordinates
Window on/off              - Turns the window on/off using previous coordinates.
Chd {Path}                 - Sets the transfer work directory
Chddef {Path}              - Sets the default transfer work directory, used
                             when error using directory Chd.
AutoChd {Path}             - Sets the Auto transfer directory path.
Errorlog                   - Turns the logfile on
Doctool {path:tool}        - Sets a textview tool for the HLink documentation
Delay 1                    - Lets HLink wait after each filetransfer for 1/50th
                             seconds per 5 Kilobytes.
Autodelay 1500             - Set the Autotransfer check period to 30 seconds.
ETAdelay 1500              - Set the ETA update period to 30 seconds.
Beep on                    - On every start/end or initiation of a transfer
                             a beep sound will be made.
Lowmem off                 - All transfers wil be done from or to memory


My configuration looks like this :

@{b}
;HLink V2.0  configuration
name Ren from the secret place ...
serspeed 38400
serblock 2048
window 80/150/500/10
doctool dh0:utilities/multiview
chddef D:
chd D:
autochd SD:
{hidden}
autosend 500
etadelay 1500
beep on
@{ub}
@endnode


@node "Remote DOS commands"

@{b}@{i}Remote DOS commands@{ui}@{ub} :

When a remote DOS command is made to the remote system it's remote shell
feedback is stored remotely in HL:feedback. After execution of this command
the feedback file will be sended to the instructing station.

To execute an remote command use :
  > com dir DH0:

This command will tell the remote station to send back an directory listing
of it's own DH0: disk.


!@{b}WARNING@{ub}  : When using remote dos commands else then dir or list without
            a path, it will be executed in the root of the bootdisk.
            Therefor it's is always neccesary to specify a path in the
            command.

!@{b}REMEMBER@{ub} : The DOS commands dir and list are if given without a path
            executed in the current workdirectory (chd).


!@{b}WARNING@{ub}  : Some commands require the user to enter a key (like format),
            it is not possible to forfill this remote request. Use an
            remote placed @{"HLink Script" Link "HLink Scripts"} to avoid any problems.



@endnode


@node "File Transfer"

@{b}@{i}File Transfer@{ui}@{ub} :

When a @{"Send" Link "HLink Syntaxes"} commando is given the filenames that are to be send are stored
in the file HL:transfer. After this the filenames will be read, processed
and the HL:transfer file will be deleted.

The files are send in single blocks, the block size is adjustable but
goes hand-in-hand with the transfer reliability (so does the baudrate).

The estimated time (E.T.A.) for a transfer is calculated using pre-set
values, therefor there can be a slight difference. The maximum possible
is around 4Kb per second, this is at the highest baudrate.

For large files there is an E.T.A. update option, this is set using the
ETAdelay command. After this period the new E.T.A. will be displayed.

When specifying the files to transfer all wildcards are allowed, this is
because the wildcard is used with a list command to locate all the files
and there size.

Further there is an additional file transfer work path wich can be assigned
using the "Com Chd {path}" shell command. Any received files will end up
in this directory.

The possibility that a file transfer fails is always there, for this purpose
there is a user-setting 'RequestAgain', when this is set 'on' the receiving
station will keep requesting the file until received succesfull.


@{b}!REMEMBER@{ub} : Files with spaces in there names can't be transferred, this is
            because DOS can't identify them, rename the files and try again.

@{b}!REMEMBER@{ub} : When transfering a single file without a path name the
            chd path is used as a source path.

@{b}!WARNING@{ub}  : When the processor has a high taskload timeout error may
            occur when transferring large files. A solution is to
            set the priority of other programs lower then that of HLink.


There is also the @{"Auto Transfer" Link "Auto Transfer"} directory SD:  Any file or directory placed
here will be transferred to the remote station.

@endnode



@node "Auto Transfer"

@{b}Automatic Directory Transfer@{ub} :

By using the SD: directory it is possible to let HLink transfer the placed
directory's or files automaticly. HLink will check at a set period of time
if there are any objects available in SD: an starts transfering them.

A difference is that the files that are succesfully sended will be deleted.
Any file or directory that fails an transfer will be noted and tried again
at a later stage. This process will not stop until you remove the faulty
file yourself.

An problem with faulty files is that if you have triggered the Errorlog it
will be filled with transfer errors of the faulty file. This log can grow
very rapidly if the @{"AutoSend" Link "HLink Syntaxes"} setting is set at a short period.


@{b}!WARNING@{ub} : Don't build archives in this directory cause they will be
           transferred as soon as possible, this means that only the
           current archived part will be send.


                         @(" Main menu " Link "Main menu"}

                         @{" Features  " Link "Features"}
@endnode


@node "Lowmem Transfer"

@{b}Low memory / File-to-file transfers@{ub} :

First of all I have to say that every file larger then 2MB automaticly
triggers the Lowmem transfer mechanism. This means that the file will
be transmitted in parts, each one loaded, transmitted and saved one by
one. This, of coarse leads to an decrease of overall speed.

When activated a data buffer is reserved, this buffer will not be larger
then 65 Kb and is accessed for quick loading and saving of file data.

The E.T.A. time is not so accurate because is was impossible to estimate
the average load and save delays on all the available harddisks.

@{b}!WARNING@{ub} : When using this lowmem transfer mode with certain
            file sizes you need the included Join command to
            join parts that can't be equally divided.

@endnode


@node "HLink Scripts"

@{b}@{i}HLink Scripts@{ui}@{ub} :

When you want to execute a remote batchscript, do the following :

  - make a script with the neccesary commands
  - use the following extension @{b}.hl@{ub} , DON'T USE SPACES IN THE NAME !
  - place it on the remote machine in the HLink: directory
  - if wanted place it on the local machine in the HLink: directory
  - when calling the remote script enter it's name including the .al extension

The remote machine will now check if a file with that name exist in it's local
HLink: directory, if it does it will be executed.


I have been trying some nice things with these scripts, the ability to execute
DOS commands remotly can be very handy indeed. Myself have installed a couple
of icons with IconX'ed script that command HLink to do almost anything you
could do from a CLI window.

For the ancient capacity problem I had to place some programs on one of my
other harddisk systems. To still be able to use it on the first system,
I have made an script wich installs the program on the intitiated system and
starts it up. Afterwards the programs and it's files can be removed by another
iconX file or batchfile.

I have included some example remote-install script wich installs and runs
OctaMED on a remote system within 2 minits. And only by initiating one script.
These examples are in the NetScripts directory when unpacking the HLink2.Lha
archive.


@{b}!WARNING@{ub} : When using scripts wich contain multiple commands make sure that
           there is a delay (Wait xx) between commands that remotely acces
           a diskdrive (hard or floppy). If not HLink can get rushed into sending
           while the remote station is not yet ready resorting to Serial errors.

@endnode


@node "Net Scripts"

@{b}Network scripts@{ub} :

By using batchscripts it's possible to echo commands to the HL:execute command
file of HLink. Now you can build such a script wich will transfer an entire
application (program, configs, data) to another station.

See the examples for Octamed and Megalosound in the HLink:NetScripts directory.

@{b}!WARNING@{ub} : When using scripts wich contain multiple commands make sure that
           there is a delay (Wait xx) between commands that remotely acces
           a diskdrive (hard or floppy). If not HLink can get rushed into sending
           while the remote station is not yet ready resorting to Serial errors.


@endnode


@node "Trouble Shooting"

@{b}Trouble Shooting@{ub} :

Problems can arise at the most unexpected moments, so here's a small list
of knowm problems and there solutions.

* I keep having transfer-timeouts    >>   Set the Delay value higher and try
                                          again, repeat till normal.

@endnode



@node "Bug Report"

@{b}Bug Reports@{ub} :

23 June 1996 - The 'AutoDelay' command is renamed to 'Autosend'.
               The parameters are not changed.

28 July 1996 - Using the SEND command in capitals is now possible.

01 July 1996 - When given a SEND command without a pathname all the files
               in the D: directory where send, this is corrected.

26 July 1996 - Automatic transferred directory's were not deleted. Fixed.


@endnode


